The worst case time complexity of a binary tree sort is O(n log n). This is because in the worst case, the input data is already sorted and each comparison leads to a binary branch, resulting in a total of n log n comparisons.

In the worst case, the time complexity cannot be O(n) or O(n^2) because the number of comparisons is less than or more than n log n, respectively.

In the worst case, the time complexity cannot be O(log n) because the number of comparisons is greater than log n.

It is important to note that this is the worst case time complexity, and the actual time complexity can be different depending on the input data and implementation. Additionally, there are other sorts that may have better worst case time complexity, but the binary tree sort is a commonly used and efficient sort when the input data is already sorted or partially sorted.

data.sampled:
**c**

It is important that you understand why Bubble Sort is an unstable sort.  When A and B are adjacent, and if A changes places with B (this may require moving A to the end of the list temporarily, but A can never move past B), then the order of the original list will be the same after it has been sorted... except that A will appear after B in the sorted list.  
So if A and B appear to have their values in reverse order in the original list, flipping them with a bubble sort will reverse it. 

The bubble sort is unstable because if A and B are in reverse order, and B comes before A, the bubble sort can accidentally reverse them; and for a naive implementation it can never swap B and C if B is between A and C -- the bubble sort can go into an infinite loop.
 
So the choice **c** is correct.
